grep stands for Global Regular Expression Print.

It is a Linux command used to search text or patterns inside

cat > student.txt                # Opens the file to enter data
1 Sahil 85
2 Umar 78
3 Afan 92
4 Nazif 67
Ctrl + D                         # Saves the file and exits

grep "Sahil" student.txt
# Searches and prints the line containing "Sahil"

grep "92" student.txt
# Searches and prints the line containing 92

grep -i "sahil" student.txt
# -i means ignore case
# Searches "sahil", "SAHIL", "Sahil", etc.

grep -n "Umar" student.txt
# -n means line number
# Prints the matching line along with its line number

grep -v "Nazif" student.txt
# -v means inverse search
# Prints all lines except the line containing "Nazif"
